For any derivation in the grammar, the start symbol S must first expand as

S → NT6 NT58

Consequently, the generated string must begin with whatever NT6 can produce.

The only production for NT6 is

NT6 → NT73 NT62

Terminal possibilities for these constituents are:
• NT73 → 't25'                (one token)
• NT73 → NT8 NT9 → 't12' ('t26' | 't3')   (two tokens)
• NT62 → 't84' | 't97'        (one token)

Hence every string generated by NT6 must begin with either
  t25 …  or  t12 …

The target string begins with the token t6.

Since t6 cannot be the first token generated by NT6, the entire string cannot be derived from the grammar. Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.

No

The start symbol S must expand according to the only rule
S → NT6 NT58.

Therefore the string produced by the grammar must consist of
(1) a block generated by NT6 followed immediately by
(2) a block generated by NT58.

NT6, however, has exactly one rule:

NT6 → NT73 NT62

• NT62 is a single‑terminal non‑terminal: NT62 → t84 | t97  
  → length 1.

• NT73 can be either  
  NT73 → t25 (length 1) or NT73 → NT8 NT9 (length 2)
  with NT8 → t12 and NT9 → t26 | t3.  
  So NT73 yields either the single token t25 or the two‑token
  sequence t12 t26 / t12 t3.

Consequently NT6 can generate only
  • t25 t84, t25 t97 (length 2), or
  • t12 t26 t84, t12 t26 t97, t12 t3 t84, t12 t3 t97 (length 3).

The given string begins with
t12 t77 …

None of the six possible prefixes produced by NT6 matches the initial segment of the string (they would have to start with t25 or with t12 t26/t3 followed by t84/t97).

Since NT6 cannot account for the required prefix, the start symbol S cannot derive the entire string, and the string is not in the language.

No

To start a derivation the grammar forces  

S ⇒ NT6 NT58.  

NT6 has only one rule: NT6 ⇒ NT73 NT62.

• NT73 can give either  
 – the single terminal t25, or  
 – the two‑terminal sequence t12 (t26 | t3).  

• NT62 can give the single terminal t84 or t97.  

Hence every sentential form produced by NT6 is one of

1. t25 t84  
2. t25 t97  
3. t12 t26 t84  
4. t12 t26 t97  
5. t12 t3 t84  
6. t12 t3 t97.

So any string generated by the grammar must begin with one of those exact prefixes.  
The given string begins with t12 t36…, which matches none of them, therefore NT6 cannot derive the initial part of the string and S cannot derive the whole string.

Hence the grammar does not generate the supplied string.

No

The start symbol S must first produce NT6, so the string has to begin with whatever NT6 can generate.

NT6 → NT73 NT62  
NT73 → 't25' | NT8 NT9  
NT62 → 't84' | 't97'  

Therefore NT6 can only produce:

• two‑token sequence:  t25  t84  
• two‑token sequence:  t25  t97  
• three‑token sequence: t25  t12  t26 (followed by t84 or t97, giving t25 t12 t26 t84 or t25 t12 t26 t97)

The given string starts with “t25 t82 …”.  
None of the possible outputs of NT6 begins with “t25 t82”.  
Because S → NT6 NT58, the derivation must start with NT6’s output, so the grammar cannot match the provided string.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT6 NT58  

so every derivation must begin with a string generated by NT6.

NT6 has exactly one rule:  

NT6 → NT73 NT62

NT62 can only produce a single terminal (t84 or t97).  
NT73 can produce either
• t25, or  
• NT8 NT9, where NT8 → t12 and NT9 is expanded later.

Thus the very first token produced by NT6 is either t25 (if NT73 → t25) or t12 (if NT73 → NT8 NT9 and NT8 → t12).

Our target string begins with t12, so we must use the second alternative:
NT73 ⇒ NT8 NT9 ⇒ t12 (…).

Consequently, the second token of the whole string must be the first token produced by NT9.

But NT9 has only the following possibilities:

NT9 → t26  
NT9 → t3  
NT9 → NT68 NT40  (and NT68 starts with either t36 or t36 again via NT63)

None of these options can start with t14, which is the actual second token of the given string.

Therefore NT6 cannot generate the required prefix “t12 t14…”, so S cannot derive the whole string.

Hence the grammar does not generate the provided string.

No

To obtain the whole string the start symbol must expand exactly as

S ⇒ NT6 NT58

Since there is only one rule for NT6,

NT6 ⇒ NT73 NT62

and NT73 and NT62 can generate only the following terminal strings:

NT73 ⇒ t25                                   (length 1)
NT73 ⇒ NT8 NT9 ⇒ t12 t3               (length 2)

NT62 ⇒ t84  or  t97                      (length 1)

Hence NT6 can produce only two possible terminal strings:

1. t25 t84   or  t25 t97               (length 2)
2. t12 t3 t84  or  t12 t3 t97       (length 3)

Because S places the substring from NT6 at the very beginning of the overall string, the first two or three symbols of the target string would have to match one of these four possibilities.  
But the string we need to check begins with

t12 t77 …,

which matches none of them. Therefore no derivation from the grammar can yield the given string.

No

The start symbol expands as  

S → NT6 NT58  

NT58 then expands as  

NT58 → NT84 NT9  

so the very last part of any string generated by the grammar must be produced by NT9.

The only ways NT9 can produce terminals are  
1. NT9 → 't26'  
2. NT9 → 't3'  
3. NT9 → NT68 NT40, where each of NT68 and NT40 yields at least two terminals.  
   In every such case the right‑most terminal is either  
   • 't96' (from NT17 or NT66), or  
   • 't72' (from NT56), or  
   • 't77' / 't8' (from NT74).

Consequently NT9 can never end with the terminal 't94'.

The given string ends with the terminal t94, so it cannot be produced by NT9, hence cannot be produced by NT58, and therefore cannot be produced by S.

Thus the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  
S → NT6 NT58.

Thus the first part of every word generated by the grammar is produced by NT6.

NT6 has exactly one rule:  
NT6 → NT73 NT62.

Examine the rules for NT73 and NT62:

• NT73 → 't25'  
• NT73 → NT8 NT9 with NT8 → 't12' and NT9 → 't26' | 't3'.

Hence NT73 can yield only the sequences  
t25  
t12 t26  
t12 t3.

• NT62 → 't84' | 't97' (single token).

Therefore NT6 can generate only one of the following token sequences:

1. t25 t84  
2. t25 t97  
3. t12 t26 t84  
4. t12 t26 t97  
5. t12 t3 t84  
6. t12 t3 t97.

In every case the very first token produced by NT6 (and thus by the whole sentence) must be either t25 or t12.

The given string begins with t74.

Since t74 can never be the first token of a string derived from NT6, the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

The start symbol S expands once and only once as  

S → NT6 NT58  

Thus every sentence in the language is the concatenation of a word produced by NT6 followed immediately by a word produced by NT58.

NT58, in turn, can expand only in one of two CNF ways:

1. NT58 → 't46' (the entire NT58‑part is the single terminal t46), or  
2. NT58 → NT84 NT9     (the NT58‑part is the concatenation of a word of NT84 followed by a word of NT9).

The given 48‑token string contains no t46 token, so alternative 1 is impossible; NT58 must realise alternative 2.  
Consequently, the last part of the whole string (after whatever NT6 produces) has to be the yield of NT9, i.e. the very last token of the whole sentence must be the final token produced by NT9.

Now look at every possible terminal that NT9 can finish with.

• NT9 → 't26'             ⇒ ends with t26  
• NT9 → 't3'              ⇒ ends with t3  
• NT9 → NT68 NT40  

  – NT40 → NT69 NT17 ⇒ ends with NT17 ⇒ 't96'  
  – NT40 → NT74 NT56  

    * NT56 → 't72'                         ⇒ ends with t72  
    * NT56 → NT9 NT19 (ends with NT19)   ⇒ NT19 always ends with t67 or t13  
    * NT56 → NT95 NT36 (ends with NT36)   ⇒ NT36 ends with t9, t70, t6, t44, t64 or t79

Hence NT9 can end only with one of the following terminals:  
t26, t3, t96, t72, t67, t13, t9, t70, t6, t44, t64 or t79.  

The string we must parse, however, ends with

… t72 t67 t94

so its very last symbol is t94.

Because t94 is not among the possible final symbols of any word generated by NT9, the required decomposition

string = (word of NT6) · (word of NT84) · (word of NT9)

is impossible. Therefore the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No

The derivation of any string from the start symbol S must begin with the left‑most non‑terminal in S’s only production:

S → NT6 NT58

Hence the first token of every string in the language is the first token produced by NT6.

NT6 has only one rule:

NT6 → NT73 NT62

Consequently the first token produced by NT6 is the first token produced by NT73.

The rules for NT73 are

NT73 → 't25'
NT73 → NT8 NT9          (with NT8 → 't12')

Thus the first token derivable from NT73 (and hence from NT6 and from S) can be either t25 or t12, and no other terminal.

The string we are asked to recognise starts with t13.  
Because t13 ≠ t25 and t13 ≠ t12, the first token of the given string cannot be generated by NT6, and therefore the whole string cannot be generated by S.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
